{"title_page": "Euteleostomi", "text_new": "{{automatic taxobox\n| name= Euteleostomes\n| fossil_range = [[Silurian]] - [[Holocene|Present]], {{fossilrange|420|0}}\n| image =Vertebrates.png\n| image_caption = Individual organisms from each major Euteleostomi group. Clockwise, starting from top left:\n[[Fire salamander]] (Amphibia), [[saltwater crocodile]] (Reptilia), [[southern cassowary]] (Aves), [[Rhynchocyon petersi|black-and-rufous giant elephant shrew]] (Mammalia), [[ocean sunfish]] (Osteichthyes)\n| taxon = Euteleostomi\n| subdivision_ranks = Subgroups\n| subdivision = \n*[[Actinopterygii]]\n*[[Sarcopterygii]]\n}}\n\n'''Euteleostomi''' is a successful [[clade]] that includes more than 90% of the living species of vertebrates.  '''Euteleostomes''' are also known as \"bony [[vertebrate]]s\".  Both its major subgroups are successful today: Actinopterygii includes the majority of [[Extant taxon|extant]] fish species, and Sarcopterygii includes the [[tetrapod]]s.\n\n\"[[Osteichthyes]]\" in the sense of \"bony vertebrates\" is synonymous with Euteleostomi<ref name=\"FishesWorld\">{{cite book|last1=Nelson|first1=Joseph|title=Fishes of the World|url=https://books.google.dk/books?id=exTV-GLnCB4C|date=2007|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=0-471-75644-X|page=86}}</ref>, even though in [[Linnaean taxonomy]] the name (literally meaning \"bony fish\") traditionally referred to the [[paraphyletic]] group with the exclusion of tetrapods.<ref name=\"HistoryUniversity2004\">{{cite book|last1=Cracraft|first1=Joel|last2=Donoghue|first2=Michael J. |title=Assembling the Tree of Life|url=https://books.google.dk/books?id=MhaVDwAAQBAJ|date=25 April 2019|publisher=Academic Press|isbn=978-0-19-972960-9|page=396}}</ref> The name Euteleostomi was coined as a monophyletic alternative that unambiguously includes the living tetrapods and is widely used in bioinformatics<ref name=\"Bioinformatics\">{{cite book|last1=Berman|first1=Jules||title=Evolution's Clinical Guidebook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6lXTP0YU6_kC&pg=PA396|accessdate=14 May 2015|date=25 June 2004|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0-12-817127-8|page=215}}</ref>. \n\nThe term Euteleostomi comes from ''Eu-[[teleostomi]]'', where \"Eu-\" comes from the [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] \u03b5\u1f56 meaning ''well'' or ''good'', so the clade can be defined as the living [[teleostomes]].\n\nEuteleostomes originally all had [[endochondral]] bone, fins with [[Lepidotrichia|lepidotrich]]s (fin rays), jaws lined by [[maxilla]]ry, [[premaxillary]], and dentary bones composed of [[dermal bone]], and [[Lung#Origins of the vertebrate lung|lungs]].  Many of these characters have since been lost by descendant groups, however, such as lepidotrichs lost in [[tetrapod]]s, and bone lost among the [[Chondrostei|chondrostean]] fishes. Lungs have been retained in dipnoi (lungfish), and many tetrapods (birds, mammals, reptiles, and some amphibians). In many ray-finned fishes lungs have evolved into swim bladders for regulating buoyancy, while in others they continue to be used as respiratory gas bladders.<ref name=\"Clack2012\">{{cite book |last=Clack |first=Jennifer A.|authorlink=Jenny Clack|title=Gaining Ground, Second Edition: The Origin and Evolution of Tetrapods |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4j9AKGsQ1msC&pg=PA23|accessdate=12 May 2015|date=27 June 2012 |publisher=Indiana University Press |isbn=0-253-00537-X |pages=21\u20134}}</ref><ref name=\"LongoRiccio2013\">{{cite journal |last1=Longo |first1=Sarah |last2=Riccio |first2=Mark |last3=McCune |first3=Amy R |title=Homology of lungs and gas bladders: Insights from arterial vasculature|journal=Journal of Morphology |volume=274 |issue=6 |year=2013 |pages=687\u2013703 |issn=0362-2525 |doi=10.1002/jmor.20128 |pmid=23378277}}</ref><ref name=\"R. McCuneC. Schimenti2012\">{{cite journal |last1=R. McCune|first1=Amy|last2=C. Schimenti|first2=John |title=Using Genetic Networks and Homology to Understand the Evolution of Phenotypic Traits|journal=Current Genomics |volume=13 |issue=1 |year=2012 |pages=74\u201384 |issn=1389-2029 |doi=10.2174/138920212799034785 |pmid=22942677 |pmc=3269019}}</ref>\n\n==Classification==\nEuteleostomi contains the following subgroups:\n\n'''[[Actinopterygii]]'''\n*[[Actinopteri]]\n**[[Chondrostei]]\n**[[Neopterygii]]\n*[[Cladistia]]\n**[[Polypteriformes]]\n'''[[Sarcopterygii]]'''\n*[[Actinistia]]\n**[[Coelacanthiformes]]\n*[[Dipnoi]]\n**[[Ceratodontimorpha]]\n*[[Tetrapodomorpha]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://tolweb.org/Gnathostomata/14843.html Gnathostomata at the Tree of Life]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1378800}}\n\n[[Category:Vertebrate taxonomy]]\n[[Category:Teleostomi]]\n[[Category:Pridoli first appearances]]\n[[Category:Extant Silurian first appearances]]\n\n\n{{Vertebrate-stub}}\n\n[[es:Euteleostomi]]\n", "text_old": "{{automatic taxobox\n| name= Euteleostomes\n| fossil_range = [[Silurian]] - [[Holocene|Present]], {{fossilrange|420|0}}\n| image =Vertebrates.png\n| image_caption = Individual organisms from each major Euteleostomi group. Clockwise, starting from top left:\n[[Fire salamander]] (Amphibia), [[saltwater crocodile]] (Reptilia), [[southern cassowary]] (Aves), [[Rhynchocyon petersi|black-and-rufous giant elephant shrew]] (Mammalia), [[ocean sunfish]] (Osteichthyes)\n| taxon = Euteleostomi\n| subdivision_ranks = Subgroups\n| subdivision = \n*[[Actinopterygii]]\n*[[Sarcopterygii]]\n}}\n\n'''Euteleostomi''' is a successful [[clade]] that includes more than 90% of the living species of vertebrates.  '''Euteleostomes''' are also known as \"bony [[vertebrate]]s\".  Both its major subgroups are successful today: Actinopterygii includes the majority of [[Extant taxon|extant]] fish species, and Sarcopterygii includes the [[tetrapod]]s.\n\n\"[[Osteichthyes]]\" in the sense of \"bony vertebrates\" is synonymous with Euteleostomi<ref name=\"FishesWorld\">{{cite book|last1=Nelson|first1=Joseph|title=Fishes of the World|url=https://books.google.dk/books?id=exTV-GLnCB4C|accessdate=03 April 2020|date=2007|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=047175644X, 9780471756446|page=86}}</ref>, even though in [[Linnaean taxonomy]] the name (literally meaning \"bony fish\") traditionally referred to the [[paraphyletic]] group with the exclusion of tetrapods.<ref name=\"HistoryUniversity2004\">{{cite book|last1=Cracraft|first1=Joel|last2=Donoghue|first2=Michael J. |title=Assembling the Tree of Life|url=https://books.google.dk/books?id=MhaVDwAAQBAJ|accessdate=03 April 2020|date=25 April 2019|publisher=Academic Press|isbn=978-0-19-972960-9|page=396}}</ref> The name Euteleostomi was coined as a monophyletic alternative that unambiguously includes the living tetrapods and is widely used in bioinformatics<ref name=\"Bioinformatics\">{{cite book|last1=Berman|first1=Jules||title=Evolution's Clinical Guidebook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6lXTP0YU6_kC&pg=PA396|accessdate=14 May 2015|date=25 June 2004|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0128171278, 9780128171271|page=215}}</ref>. \n\nThe term Euteleostomi comes from ''Eu-[[teleostomi]]'', where \"Eu-\" comes from the [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] \u03b5\u1f56 meaning ''well'' or ''good'', so the clade can be defined as the living [[teleostomes]].\n\nEuteleostomes originally all had [[endochondral]] bone, fins with [[Lepidotrichia|lepidotrich]]s (fin rays), jaws lined by [[maxilla]]ry, [[premaxillary]], and dentary bones composed of [[dermal bone]], and [[Lung#Origins of the vertebrate lung|lungs]].  Many of these characters have since been lost by descendant groups, however, such as lepidotrichs lost in [[tetrapod]]s, and bone lost among the [[Chondrostei|chondrostean]] fishes. Lungs have been retained in dipnoi (lungfish), and many tetrapods (birds, mammals, reptiles, and some amphibians). In many ray-finned fishes lungs have evolved into swim bladders for regulating buoyancy, while in others they continue to be used as respiratory gas bladders.<ref name=\"Clack2012\">{{cite book |last=Clack |first=Jennifer A.|authorlink=Jenny Clack|title=Gaining Ground, Second Edition: The Origin and Evolution of Tetrapods |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4j9AKGsQ1msC&pg=PA23|accessdate=12 May 2015|date=27 June 2012 |publisher=Indiana University Press |isbn=0-253-00537-X |pages=21\u20134}}</ref><ref name=\"LongoRiccio2013\">{{cite journal |last1=Longo |first1=Sarah |last2=Riccio |first2=Mark |last3=McCune |first3=Amy R |title=Homology of lungs and gas bladders: Insights from arterial vasculature|journal=Journal of Morphology |volume=274 |issue=6 |year=2013 |pages=687\u2013703 |issn=0362-2525 |doi=10.1002/jmor.20128 |pmid=23378277}}</ref><ref name=\"R. McCuneC. Schimenti2012\">{{cite journal |last1=R. McCune|first1=Amy|last2=C. Schimenti|first2=John |title=Using Genetic Networks and Homology to Understand the Evolution of Phenotypic Traits|journal=Current Genomics |volume=13 |issue=1 |year=2012 |pages=74\u201384 |issn=1389-2029 |doi=10.2174/138920212799034785 |pmid=22942677 |pmc=3269019}}</ref>\n\n==Classification==\nEuteleostomi contains the following subgroups:\n\n'''[[Actinopterygii]]'''\n*[[Actinopteri]]\n**[[Chondrostei]]\n**[[Neopterygii]]\n*[[Cladistia]]\n**[[Polypteriformes]]\n'''[[Sarcopterygii]]'''\n*[[Actinistia]]\n**[[Coelacanthiformes]]\n*[[Dipnoi]]\n**[[Ceratodontimorpha]]\n*[[Tetrapodomorpha]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://tolweb.org/Gnathostomata/14843.html Gnathostomata at the Tree of Life]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1378800}}\n\n[[Category:Vertebrate taxonomy]]\n[[Category:Teleostomi]]\n[[Category:Pridoli first appearances]]\n[[Category:Extant Silurian first appearances]]\n\n\n{{Vertebrate-stub}}\n\n[[es:Euteleostomi]]\n", "name_user": "Amphioxys", "label": "safe", "comment": "whoops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euteleostomi"}
